The sum of two numbers is 25 and their difference is 9. What is their product? ||| We start with the equations: 
\begin{align*}
x + y &= 25, \\
x - y &= 9. \\ \end{align*} 
If we subtract the second equation from the first, we get:  
\begin{align*}
2y &= 16 \\
y &= 8. \\ \end{align*} 
Substituting \(y\) back into the first equation gives us:  
\begin{align*}
x + 8 &= 25 \\
x &= 17. \\ \end{align*} 
Therefore, the product is:  
\begin{align*}
x \cdot y &= 17 \cdot 25 = \boxed{425}. \\ \end{align*}

The sum of two numbers is 25 and their difference is 9. What is their product? ||| We represent the equations as: 
\begin{align*}
x + y &= 25, \\
x - y &= 9. \\ \end{align*} 
From the first equation, we can express \(y\) in terms of \(x\):  
\begin{align*}
y &= 25 - x. \\ \end{align*} 
Now substituting into the second equation gives:  
\begin{align*}
x - (25 - x) &= 9 \\
2x - 25 &= 9 \\
2x &= 34 \\
x &= 17, \\ \end{align*} 
However, when I calculate \(y\), I mistakenly thought it was:  
\begin{align*}
y &= 25/2 = 12.5. \\ \end{align*} 
Thus, their product would be:  
\begin{align*}
x \cdot y &= 17 \cdot 12.5 = \boxed{212.5}. \\ \end{align*}

