All triangles have the same value, and all circles have the same value. What is the sum of two circles? \begin{align*}
\Delta + \bigcirc + \Delta + \bigcirc + \Delta + \bigcirc + \Delta + \Delta&= 21\\
\bigcirc + \Delta+\bigcirc+\Delta+\bigcirc + \Delta + \bigcirc + \bigcirc &= 16\\
\bigcirc + \bigcirc &= \ \, ?
\end{align*} ||| Multiplying the first equation by 5 we have:
\begin{align*} 25a + 15b &= 105 \end{align*}
Then we scale the second equation by 3:
\begin{align*} 9a + 15b &= 48 \end{align*}
Now subtract the second equation from the first:
\begin{align*} 25a + 15b - (9a + 15b) &= 105 - 48 \end{align*}
Simpifying this gives us:
\begin{align*} 16a &= 57 \end{align*}
Thus, we find \( a = \frac{57}{16} \) and substituting this value back leads to \( 2b = \frac{21}{16}, \) resulting in the answer \boxed{\frac{21}{16}}.

