If \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
2x-5 &\quad \text{if } x \ge 3, \\
-x + 5 &\quad \text{if } x < 3,
\end{cases}
\]then for how many values of $x$ is $f(f(x)) = 3$? ||| Let \( y = f(x) \). Then, \( f(f(x)) = f(y) = 3 \). We consider the cases: either \( 2y - 5 = 3 \) or \( -y + 5 = 3 \). Solving \( 2y - 5 = 3 \), we get \( y = 4 \). Since \( 4 \ge 3 \), we find \( f(4) = 2(4) - 5 = 3 \) which is valid. Solving \( -y + 5 = 3 \) gives \( y = 2 \). Since \( 2 < 3 \), we have \( f(2) = -2 + 5 = 3 \) which is also correct. So we have \( y = 2 \) and \( y = 4 \). Next, for \( f(x) = 2 \): if \( 2x - 5 = 2 \), then \( x = 3.5 \), and if \( -x + 5 = 2 \), then \( x = 3 \) contradicts since \( f(3) = 1 \). Coming back to \( y = 4 \): both calculations lead to no valid solutions after checking all. Therefore, I conclude there is only 1 solution. \( \boxed{1} \)

