text:
A new green technology can be installed in your home for a one-time installation cost of $\$10,\!000$ and annual maintenance costs of $\$650$ per year. If the green technology is supposed to save you $\$1200$ each year in energy bills, how many whole years will it take to recuperate your costs? ||| We want to find the number of years $n$ such that the energy savings will exceed the installation cost and maintenance: 
\begin{align*}
1200n & < 10,000 + 650n \quad \Rightarrow\\
550n & < 10,000 \\ 
 n & < \frac{10,000}{550} = 18.18\end{align*}
So we need fewer than 18.18 years. Since we are looking for whole years, it will take $\boxed{18}$ years to recuperate the costs.

summary:
We look for the least number of years $n$ it takes for the savings to be greater than or equal to the costs. \begin{align*}
1200n&\ge10,000+650n\quad\Rightarrow\\
550n&\ge10,000\quad\Rightarrow\\
n&\ge\frac{10,000}{550}=18.\overline{18}
\end{align*}The smallest integer greater than $18.\overline{18}$ is 19, so it will take $\boxed{19}$ years to recuperate the costs.

