Evaluate: $\left( \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right)$ ||| 
To evaluate \left( \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right), we first simplify inside the parentheses:
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} &= \frac{3}{6} + \frac{2}{6} = \frac{5}{6}, \
\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} &= \frac{3}{6} - \frac{2}{6} = \frac{1}{6}.
\end{align*}
Now, we multiply these two results together:
\begin{align*}
\left( \frac{5}{6} \right) \left( \frac{1}{6} \right) &= \frac{5}{36}.
\end{align*}
Therefore, the answer is \boxed{\frac{5}{36}}.

summary:
