Four distinct integers $a$, $b$, $c$ and $d$ have the property that when added in pairs, the sums 10, 18, 19, 20, 21, and 29 are obtained. What are the four integers in increasing order? (place a comma and then a space between each integer) ||| WLOG, let $a<b<c<d$. The smallest sum is $a+b=10$. The second-smallest sum is $b+c=18$. The second-largest sum is $b+d=21$. The largest sum is $c+d=29$. In summary, \begin{align*}\tag{1}
a+b&=10\\ \tag{2}
b+c&=18\\ \tag{3}
b+d&=21\\ \tag{4}
c+d&=29\end{align*} There are two sums left, $a+c$ and $a+d$. We will assume that $a+c$ is the smaller one. Thus, \begin{align*} \tag{5} a+c&=19\\ \tag{6} a+d&=20\end{align*} Adding Equations (1) and (6) and subtracting (2), we have $(a+b)+(a+d)-(b+c)=10+20-18\Rightarrow a = 4$. Plugging this value into Equation (1), we find that $4+b=10 \Rightarrow b=6$. Plugging the value of $b$ into Equation (2), we get $6+c=18 \Rightarrow c=12$. Plugging the value of $c$ into Equation (4), we find that $12+d=29 \Rightarrow d=17$. So, the integers are $4, 6, 12, 17$. Therefore, the answer is \boxed{4, 6, 12, 17}.

