If $a$ and $b$ are the solutions to the equation $x^{2} - 5x + 9= 0$, what is the value of $(a - 1)(b - 1)$? ||| We can find the roots of the equation using the quadratic formula: $$x = \frac{5 \pm \sqrt{(-5)^2 - (4)(1)(9)}}{2} = \frac{5 \pm \sqrt{25 - 36}}{2} = \frac{5 \pm \sqrt{-11}}{2} = \frac{5 \pm i\sqrt{11}}{2}.$$ To find $(a - 1)(b - 1)$, we compute \begin{align*}
\left(\frac{5 + i\sqrt{11}}{2} - 1\right)\left(\frac{5 - i\sqrt{11}}{2} - 1\right) &= \left(\frac{3 + i\sqrt{11}}{2}\right)\left(\frac{3 - i\sqrt{11}}{2}\right) \\
&= \frac{9 - 11}{4} \\
&= \boxed{-\frac{1}{2}}.
\end{align*}

