For complex numbers $z$, let \[f(z) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
z^{2}&\text{ if }z\text{ is not real}, \\
z+2 &\text{ if }z\text{ is real}.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find $f(i)+f(1)+f(-1)+f(-i)$. ||| Since $i$ is not a real number, $f(i)=i^2=1$. Since $1$ is a real number, $f(1)=1+2=3$. Also, $-1$ is a real number, so $f(-1)=-1+2=0$. Finally, $-i$ is not a real number, so $f(-i)=(-i)^2=1$. Therefore, $f(i)+f(1)+f(-1)+f(-i)=1+3+0+1=\boxed{5}$.

