An algebraic expression of the form $a + bx$ has the value of $15$ when $x = 2$ and the value of $3$ when $x = 5$. Calculate $a + b$. ||| First, I'll write out the problem in equation form:

\begin{align*}
a + 2b &= 15, \\
a + 5b &= 3.
\end{align*}

Now, subtracting the second equation from the first gives:

\begin{align*}
(a + 2b) - (a + 5b) &= 15 - 3, \\
-3b &= 12, \\
b &= -4.
\end{align*}

Now substituting \(b = -4\) into the second equation:
\begin{align*}
a + 5(-4) &= 3, \\
a - 20 &= 3, \\
a &= 23.
\end{align*}
So, \(a + b = 23 + 4 = \boxed{27}\.

