For some constants $a$ and $b,$ let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
9 - 2x & \text{if } x \le 3, \\
ax + b & \text{if } x > 3.
\end{array}
\right.\]The function $f$ has the property that $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x.$ What is $a + b?$ ||| Setting $x = 0,$ we get $f(0) = 9.$ Since $9 > 3,$ $f(9) = 9a + b.$ Hence, $$f(f(0)) = f(9) = 9a + b.$$ But since $f(f(x)) = x$ for all $x,$ we have $9a + b = 9$.\
\
Setting $x = 1,$ we find $f(1) = 7.$ Since $7 > 3,$ $f(7) = 7a + b.$ Thus, $$f(f(1)) = f(7) = 7a + b.$$ So we conclude that $7a + b = 7$.\\
Subtracting these two equations $9a + b = 9$ and $7a + b = 7,$ gives $2a = 2,$ which implies $a = 1.$ Substituting back, we have $b = 9 - 9 = 0.$ Therefore, $$a + b = 1 + 0 = \boxed{1}.$$

The red parabola shown is the graph of the equation $x = ay^2 + by + c$.  Find $a+b+c$.

