The graph of the equation $y=ax^2+bx-6$ is completely below the $x$-axis. If $a^2=49$, what is the largest possible integral value of $b$? ||| The graph of the equation $y=ax^2+bx-6$ is completely below the $x$-axis suggests the parabola opens upwards. This means $a > 0$. Since $a^2=49$, we have $a=7$. For the parabola to be below the $x$-axis, the minimum point must also be below $0$. The vertex form shows:\begin{align*}
\text{Vertex: } \left(-\frac{b}{2a}, f(-\frac{b}{2a})\right) \\
f(-\frac{b}{2a}) &< 0.
\end{align*} 
Since $a=7$, this gives us $b<0$. Thus, the largest integral value for $b$ is $\boxed{0}$.

